{"cursor":"20617","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox book\n| name = Why do People Sing? Music in Human Evolution author = Joseph Jordania\n| genre = popular science book on human evolution publisher = Logos release_date\n| = 25 March 2011 isbn = 978-9941401862\n}} 'Why do People Sing? Music in Human Evolution' is a book on human evolution\nby Australian/Georgian ethnomusicologist and evolutionary musicologist Joseph\nJordania, published in 2011 by âLogosâ. The book is a continuation of the 2006\naward winning book by Jordania, [[Who Asked the First Question?]] Origins of\nHuman Choral Singing, Intelligence, Language and Speech.\n\nThe book discusses a wide range of topics on the evolution of human morphology\nand behavior. The central idea of the book is that the fundamental force behind\nthe evolution of hominid/human morphology and behavior was the original non-\ncontact defense strategy from predators, based on intimidation of predators and\ncompetitors through visual, audio and olfactory messages. The book proposes that\nforces of natural selection were behind such well known features of human\nmorphology and behavior, as long legs, long head hair, eyebrows, naked body,\npatches of hair on some parts of the body, sweat glands, bipedalism, prehistoric\ncannibalism, origins and function of music, dance, body painting, use of\nclothes, morality and religion. The book consists of four chapters, each\naddressing different circles of issues.\n","linknr":80,"url":"Why_do_People_Sing?_Music_in_Human_Evolution","recorded":1376422806,"links":["//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Why_do_People_Sing?_Music_in_Human_Evolution","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2C